y endothelium","Basement membrane and surfactant layer","Type I pneumocytes and red blood cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ealveolar epithelium, basement membrane, and capillary endothelium\u003C/strong\u003E form the three layers of the alveolar-capillary membrane, also known as the blood-gas barrier. This structure allows efficient gas exchange while maintaining a barrier between air and blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlveolar epithelium and capillary endothelium only\u003C/strong\u003E - This omits the essential basement membrane layer\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType I pneumocytes and red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While type I pneumocytes form part of the alveolar epithelium, red blood cells are not part of the membrane structure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasement membrane and surfactant layer\u003C/strong\u003E - Surfactant is secreted into the alveolar space but is not part of the membrane itself\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndothelium and smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - Smooth muscle is found in bronchioles but not in the alveolar-capillary membrane\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe extremely thin nature of these three layers (approximately 0.5 micrometres total) facilitates rapid gas diffusion according to partial pressure gradients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The alveolar-capillary membrane consists of three layers: alveolar epithelium, basement membrane, and capillary endothelium.","Oxygen diffuses across the alveolar-capillary membrane according to Fick\u0027s law, driven by partial pressure gradients.","The total thickness of the alveolar-capillary membrane is approximately 0.5 micrometres, allowing efficient gas exchange."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, 